Explained by King, silver - New Heads
{to the Editor:
There seems to be a misunderstanding on the part of
some students concerning the
cancer and concerts held on
our campus. The formal
cancer, in fact, are sponsored
by [lie Gadabouts committee,
an organization completely
separate in personnel and budget from the Concerts committee.
The rationale behind having
8 “big name” band for cancer
is as follows: Based on the
cost per student attending a
dance, it is cheaper to have a
wellrknown band than a “0.
name one. Leaving personal
preferences aside, more students participate in formal
cancer when big bands play,
especially in the spring, than
when small hands are looked.
As for the concerts, the come
little offers five concerts a
year, usually two in joint sponsorship with the music and
drama departments (this year,
“Brecht on Brecht” and the
Korean Dance Group.) Here in
Iowa it is very difficult to
find a recognized symphony orchestra that will tour this way,
and often the cost is very pro»
hibitlve. With the music department, however, we have tried
to offer a symphony every other year. A year ago we had
 
the St, Louis Symphony, and
next year we are planning on
the Warsaw Philharmonic.
Jazz, too, is a difficult problems. In the past, concerts our
fired by the Modern Jazz quarter. and pizza Gillespie were,
