Dr. H. Spiegelberg
Ends Order Series
Dr, members Spiegelberg, professor of philosophy at Washington University (St. Louis),
will be the last of a series of
guest centuries in the ”Inter
disciplinary Seminar on Order.”
An authority on phenomenolv
ogy, Dr. Spiegelberg will speak
on “Rules and Order” at 11
a. in. Monday in service shape1.
His major work to date is a
two-volume “The Phenomenological Movement: A Historical
Introduction.” This 735-page ef—
fort constitutes volumes five
and six in a seven~part series
written by outstanding philip
surgical scholars,
Born in Strasbourg, Germany, he has studied at Heidelberg, Freiberg, and Munich,
where he took his PhD. When
forced to leave the University
of Munich in 1937, he spent a
year of study in England before
coming to the United States.
where he has taught philosophy,
first at Swarthmore, and then
at Lawrence, before going to
Washington University,
The order seminar, directed
by Dr. Paul G. Kuntz (philosophy and religion) has been a
learning study of the basic
concept, with over 20 visiting
scholars, representing various
phases of the disciplines,
brought to the campus to lecture.
SCARLET AND BLACK
By John Wolf
The effect of natural root
greeting in trees is being studied on a college-owned farm
northeast of Grinnell by Ben
Graham (biol.) With the help of
a grant from the National Sci»
once Foundation.
Graham explained that "trees
in forests b e o o m e united
through their root systems.
Once united they are able to
transfer water, diseases, and
nutrition between one another.
There are as many as 25-30
trees in such a union.
“Our prime objective is to
determine the significance of
these unions. We have 5000
trees of white pine, red pine,
musician pine, and Norway
struct planned in various arrangements to determine the
effect of species and sharing."
The trees in the nursery were
purchased in 1960 when they
were two years old. Some root
greeting was already noticeable. .
“We hope to work out a technique to check on the extent of
greeting without having to dig
up the roots. This summer we
will begin on a interactive
trading technique.”
Graham Went on to explain
the significance of this expert»
ment. “Tile concept in the past
has been that trees are discrete
organisms. In sexuality, a tree
in a forest cannon be treated
as a separate organize.
“computers have trouble with
‘backflash’; when thinking trees
by poison, the poison often is
calculated to neighboring trees
by root grants, Dutch elm
disease and oak will are also
known to be transmitted in this
way.
”We also plan to check the
results of some Russian expert
series in root greeting. Russian
computers have tried ‘nest planning‘s,’ in which clumps of trees
are planned and allowed to
grow until their roots are
granted. Then all but the most
vigorous tree are cut away.
This tree, with its extra root
systems. is studied. Some Russian reports have claimed that
the added system is beneficial;
others say this added system is
panasonic."
Jim Frank, senior, has done
an independent project on root
grants in a stand of white pine
near omaha. Frank checked
the rate of growth in stamps
which were granted to living
trees. To Graham's surprise,
 
 
