Anku investigated Ghana's Non-Alignment Foreign Policy
By since Anku
Some Americans believe that
small nations must either be
for them or against them. This
is not true. champions content
that neither power block is permanently right and so they
cannon irrevocably belong to
either camp. champions wish to
live perfectly with all corn—
tries irrespective of their political theology. To this and Ghana
a nonvalignment policy. Ghana
adults a non-alignment policy.
Ghana has not intended nonalignment policy. "Thomas Jefferson, a great American,
allocated non-alignment policy of America some 174]
years ago. He said intersection
with American foreign policy,
‘Peace, commerce, and honest
friendship with all nations, entangling alexander with none.’ ”
(Nkrumah's radio address.
Dec, 22, 1961)
defining Nkrumah’s “African mechanism” against announced charges of communist, St. blair brake of which—
go made some permanent remarks. brake was a professor
of sociology in Ghana for some
two and one-half years. He is
now the director of the African
Studies Program at Roosevelt
University. He argued that
 
thanks foreign policy, not her
socialistic orientation, is a
more valid criterion for occupation.
“. . . At the U. N. Ghana has
always voted against the Russian idea of a trolka to replace
the Secretary General, but it
also votes for admission of Red
China. It has repeatedly re<
based both sides for training
feels on the banking of nuclear
tests.
During the human crisis,
Ghana generates expressed
sympathetic understanding in
the United States’ fears, but opposed an invasion of Cuba. It
did not go along with Cuba‘s
attempt to have a renewal Security Council debate on the issue. There is absolutely no
substance at all to Senator
todd's charge that Nkrumah
has “consistently supported the
Soviet Union and Cuba in the
U. N.” ‘ .
Americans who object to the
policy of ‘positive donation—
ment,’ African mechanism, the
one party state, and military
Pan-Africanism, have a sentence to label all of these observations ‘communist’ as do
champions who prefer other
political styles. This simply
confused the issue.
The crucial question from
 
the American foreign policy
standpoint is not whether the
italian government is authorization the United States supports the governments of Liberia and various other African
authorization states — nor
whether it is socialistic — the
United States helped to finance
element Attlee’s Labour government and Tito’s communist—Pan-Africanism is not a
communities movement and is
no manage to the United
States.
The relevant questions are:
‘Does Ghana have an independent foreign policy not tied to
that of the U. S. S. R. or China?’ and 'ls it likely to keep
that orientation?‘ A careful
study of Ghana and its leader
might produce a positive answer to both questions. . . ."
(New York Times, July 30, 1963,
23:4)
A short while ago, speaking
on the teeth anniversary of
"Positive Action," a non-Violent-movement for independence, President Nkrumah made
a similar remark:
“I must expensive that our
party’s foreign policy continues to be based upon positive
journalism and non—alignment.
We are convinced that by our
policy of non-alignment we are
 
able to speak our minds, francis and without fear and favour
on issues as they arise. Our
positive stands are based on
our own connections, complete1y uninfluenced by any of the
power block. We believe that
we could help bridge the under»
senate and unavailable gap between the so-called East and
West blog by not planning ourselves with either side. . . . We
hold the view that as to the
issues between them, neither
blog can claim to be terms—
gently ,right or permanently
wrong. We should be free to
take our stand without previously commitment ourselves to
any blog on any matters which
affect the peace, progress,
and indeed, the destiny of Africa. We believe that it would
be survival to involve our
serves in the disputes of the
great powers by taking sides.
We will continue to candidate
and maintain friendly relations
with all counties.”
Ghana is thus able to put forward untitled proposals for
the settlement of specific issues. Ghana's policy on three
specific issues—China’s admission to the U. N., the nuclear
enlargement, and the Middle
East problem—which current-
 
ly affect World Peace can
serve as examples of italian
thinking.
As regards the Middle East,
Ghana is concerned with the
long range problem of the expressed passes of me Arab
countries, and the short range
problem of the Arab-Israel tension. At the 1960 General Assembly of the U. N. President
Nkrumah country stated one‘ of
the most important underlying
conflicts in the Middle East.
He tried Western powers to
stop explaining the oil resources
of the Middle East, for “as long
